<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="654" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d654">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 611.419/33a</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-03">
                                <hi rend="italic">November 3, 1914</hi>.</date>
                        </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>454. American interests greatly desire lifting of embargoes on wool and
                            rubber. Inquire as to grounds on which these embargoes rest and whether
                            shipments might be allowed to this country from United Kingdom, its
                            colonies and settlements.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>